1
00:01:37,011 --> 00:01:39,805
<i>RAY: My father's name was
John Kinse/la.</i>

2
00:01:39,806 --> 00:01:41,723
<i>It's an Irish name.</i>

3
00:01:41,724 --> 00:01:44,309
<i>He was born
in North Dakota in 1896</i>

4
00:01:44,310 --> 00:01:49,310
<i>and never saw a big city until he
came back from France in 1918.</i>

5
00:01:49,691 --> 00:01:52,317
<i>Settling in Chicago,
he learned to live and die</i>

6
00:01:52,318 --> 00:01:54,152
<i>with the White Sox.</i>

7
00:01:54,153 --> 00:01:57,781
<i>Died a little when they
lost the 1919 World Series,</i>

8
00:01:57,782 --> 00:02:02,782
<i>died a lot when eight White Sox were
accused of throwing that Series.</i>

9
00:02:03,329 --> 00:02:06,915
<i>He played some in the minors,
but nothing came of it.</i>

10
00:02:06,916 --> 00:02:11,336
<i>Moved to Brooklyn in '35,
married Mom in '38,</i>

11
00:02:11,337 --> 00:02:14,089
<i>was already an old man
at the nava/ yards</i>

12
00:02:14,090 --> 00:02:17,092
<i>when I was born in 1952.</i>

13
00:02:17,093 --> 00:02:19,219
<i>My name's Ray Kinse/la.</i>

14
00:02:19,220 --> 00:02:23,974
<i>Mom died when I was three, and I
suppose Dad did the best he could.</i>

15
00:02:23,975 --> 00:02:28,061
<i>Instead of Mother Goose, I was put
to bed to stories of Babe Ruth,</i>

16
00:02:28,062 --> 00:02:32,316
<i>Lou Gehrig, and the great
Shoeless Joe Jackson.</i>

17
00:02:32,317 --> 00:02:36,236
<i>Dad was a Yankees fan then,
so I rooted for Brooklyn.</i>

18
00:02:36,237 --> 00:02:41,199
<i>In '58, the Dodgers moved away, so we
had to find other reasons to fight.</i>

19
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:42,534
<i>We did.</i>

20
00:02:42,535 --> 00:02:44,536
<i>When I chose a college,</i>

21
00:02:44,537 --> 00:02:48,373
<i>I picked the farthest
from home I could find.</i>

22
00:02:48,374 --> 00:02:52,961
<i>This drove him up the wall,
which, I suppose, was the point.</i>

23
00:02:52,962 --> 00:02:57,007
<i>Official/y, my major was English,
but really, it was the '60s.</i>

24
00:02:57,008 --> 00:03:00,218
<i>I marched, I smoked some grass,</i>

25
00:03:00,219 --> 00:03:04,014
<i>I tried to like sitar music,
and I met Annie.</i>

26
00:03:04,015 --> 00:03:05,891
<i>The only thing we had in common</i>

27
00:03:05,892 --> 00:03:10,812
<i>was that she came from Iowa,
and I'd once heard of/owa.</i>

28
00:03:10,813 --> 00:03:12,981
<i>After graduation,
we moved to the Midwest</i>

29
00:03:12,982 --> 00:03:15,942
<i>and stayed with her family
as long as we could,</i>

30
00:03:15,943 --> 00:03:18,904
<i>almost a full afternoon.</i>

31
00:03:18,905 --> 00:03:21,907
<i>Annie and I got married
in June of '74.</i>

32
00:03:21,908 --> 00:03:24,409
<i>Dad died that fall.</i>

33
00:03:24,410 --> 00:03:26,787
<i>A few years later,
Karin was born.</i>

34
00:03:26,788 --> 00:03:29,748
<i>She smelled weird,
but we loved her anyway.</i>

35
00:03:29,749 --> 00:03:34,749
<i>Then Annie got the crazy idea she
could talk me into buying a farm.</i>

36
00:03:35,672 --> 00:03:37,381
<i>I'm 36 years old,
I love my family,</i>

37
00:03:37,382 --> 00:03:41,593
<i>I love baseball, and I'm
about to become a farmer.</i>

38
00:03:41,594 --> 00:03:44,429
<i>But until I heard the voice,</i>

39
00:03:44,430 --> 00:03:49,430
<i>I'd never done a crazy thing
in my whole life.</i>

40
00:04:24,929 --> 00:04:29,929
<i>MALE VOICE: /fyou build it,
he will come.</i>

41
00:04:47,493 --> 00:04:52,493
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

42
00:04:59,547 --> 00:05:01,506
Hey, Annie!

43
00:05:01,507 --> 00:05:03,383
Annie, what was that?

44
00:05:03,384 --> 00:05:06,386
What was what?

45
00:05:06,387 --> 00:05:11,387
That voice just now.
What was it?

46
00:05:12,268 --> 00:05:17,268
We didn't hear anything.

47
00:05:18,149 --> 00:05:22,486
All right.

48
00:05:22,487 --> 00:05:27,487
<i>MALE VOICE: /fyou build it,
he will come.</i>

49
00:05:31,287 --> 00:05:33,455
Okay, you must have heard that!

50
00:05:33,456 --> 00:05:37,292
Sorry. Hey,
come on in to dinner.

51
00:05:37,293 --> 00:05:42,293
Let's go, pumpkin.

52
00:05:58,564 --> 00:06:01,191
Is there, like,
a sound truck on the highway?

53
00:06:01,192 --> 00:06:05,195
Nope. Hey, Karin,
dinner's ready!

54
00:06:05,196 --> 00:06:06,488
Kids with a radio?

55
00:06:06,489 --> 00:06:08,573
Nope.

56
00:06:08,574 --> 00:06:11,159
Hey, are you really
hearing voices?

57
00:06:11,160 --> 00:06:13,578
Just one.

58
00:06:13,579 --> 00:06:16,581
What did it say?

59
00:06:16,582 --> 00:06:21,582
"If you build it,
he will come."

60
00:06:21,963 --> 00:06:24,589
If you build what,
who will come?

61
00:06:24,590 --> 00:06:26,925
He didn't say.

62
00:06:26,926 --> 00:06:28,510
I hate it when that happens.

63
00:06:28,511 --> 00:06:29,055
Me, too.

64
00:06:44,527 --> 00:06:49,527
<i>MALE VOICE: /fyou build it,
he will come.</i>

65
00:07:01,961 --> 00:07:05,088
Build what? What is this?

66
00:07:05,089 --> 00:07:05,589
Ray?

67
00:07:09,760 --> 00:07:14,760
It's okay, honey. I... I'm
just talking to the cornfield.

68
00:07:18,978 --> 00:07:21,146
<i>Anyway, I was walking down
along the street,</i>

69
00:07:21,147 --> 00:07:24,149
<i>and I heard this voice saying,</i>

70
00:07:24,150 --> 00:07:26,192
<i>"Good evening, Mr. Dowd."</i>

71
00:07:26,193 --> 00:07:28,778
<i>Well, I turned around,</i>

72
00:07:28,779 --> 00:07:33,779
<i>and here was this big, six-foot rabbit
leaning up against the lamppost.</i>

73
00:07:37,413 --> 00:07:39,664
Why did you do that?
It was funny.

74
00:07:39,665 --> 00:07:42,000
Trust me, Karin.
It's not funny.

75
00:07:42,001 --> 00:07:44,461
The man is sick. Very sick.

76
00:07:44,462 --> 00:07:46,838
Karin, honey,
get your book bag. Let's go!

77
00:07:46,839 --> 00:07:49,090
Hon, I'll take her today.

78
00:07:49,091 --> 00:07:51,343
I've got errands to do in town.

79
00:07:51,344 --> 00:07:51,844
Farout.

80
00:07:56,432 --> 00:08:00,810
Hey. What if the voice calls
while you're gone?

81
00:08:00,811 --> 00:08:02,520
Take a message.

82
00:08:02,521 --> 00:08:03,647
ANNIE: (CHUCKLING) Bye.

83
00:08:03,648 --> 00:08:04,940
Bye.

84
00:08:04,941 --> 00:08:08,276
Bye.

85
00:08:08,277 --> 00:08:11,237
In all those years,
did you ever...

86
00:08:11,238 --> 00:08:14,699
It's just I've heard that
sometimes farmers in the field...

87
00:08:14,700 --> 00:08:17,452
They hear things.
You know, voices.

88
00:08:17,453 --> 00:08:18,536
You hearing voices?

89
00:08:18,537 --> 00:08:21,831
No. It's just I heard
some farmers do.

90
00:08:21,832 --> 00:08:26,832
I, of course, don't, so I was wondering
if I was doing something wrong.

91
00:08:28,089 --> 00:08:31,007
Did you... Did you ever hear
voices out there?

92
00:08:31,008 --> 00:08:32,384
Who's hearing voices?

93
00:08:32,385 --> 00:08:33,760
Ray is.

94
00:08:33,761 --> 00:08:36,137
Out in the fields. No, I'm not.

95
00:08:36,138 --> 00:08:37,472
I'm...

96
00:08:37,473 --> 00:08:39,224
(CRAZY PLAYING ON STEREO)

97
00:08:39,225 --> 00:08:40,850
(RAY LAUGHING)

98
00:08:40,851 --> 00:08:45,480
Noises. That darned tractor...

99
00:08:45,481 --> 00:08:49,484
I'm just going to get some 3-in-1 oil.
That ought to do it.

100
00:08:49,485 --> 00:08:54,485
Itwas nice...
Nice talking to you.

101
00:09:20,182 --> 00:09:23,601
<i>MALE VOICE: /fyou build it,
he will come.</i>

102
00:09:23,602 --> 00:09:28,064
All right, that's it!
Huh? Who the...

103
00:09:28,065 --> 00:09:30,525
Who are you, huh?
What do you want from me?

104
00:09:30,526 --> 00:09:31,860
Son of a...

105
00:09:31,861 --> 00:09:36,861
<i>MALE VOICE: /fyou build it,
he will come.</i>

106
00:09:36,866 --> 00:09:41,866
If you build it...

107
00:09:47,585 --> 00:09:52,585
If you build it,

108
00:09:56,177 --> 00:10:01,177
he will come.

109
00:10:25,998 --> 00:10:29,834
ANNIE: You don't suppose this is
like an acid flashback, do you?

110
00:10:29,835 --> 00:10:31,169
I never took acid.

111
00:10:31,170 --> 00:10:35,173
Maybe you will someday.
It's like a flash-forward.

112
00:10:35,174 --> 00:10:36,966
Annie, there's more.

113
00:10:36,967 --> 00:10:40,428
Honey, why don't you eat
a little bit?

114
00:10:40,429 --> 00:10:45,016
I... I think I know what "If you
build it, he will come" means.

115
00:10:45,017 --> 00:10:48,520
Why do I not think
this is so good?

116
00:10:48,521 --> 00:10:53,441
I think it means that if I build
a baseball field out there,

117
00:10:53,442 --> 00:10:58,442
Shoeless Joe Jackson will get to
come back and play ball again.

118
00:10:59,073 --> 00:11:01,449
You're kidding?

119
00:11:01,450 --> 00:11:04,160
Uh-uh.

120
00:11:04,161 --> 00:11:05,787
ANNIE: Wow.

121
00:11:05,788 --> 00:11:08,123
Yeah.

122
00:11:08,124 --> 00:11:12,669
You're kidding.

123
00:11:12,670 --> 00:11:17,382
Boy, I thought my family was crazy,
but this is the craziest thing ever.

124
00:11:17,383 --> 00:11:20,510
I know. It's totally nuts.
I mean, Shoeless Joe!

125
00:11:20,511 --> 00:11:23,221
He's dead. Died in '51.
He's dead.

126
00:11:23,222 --> 00:11:25,056
They suspended him, right?

127
00:11:25,057 --> 00:11:26,224
Right.

128
00:11:26,225 --> 00:11:27,725
He's still dead?

129
00:11:27,726 --> 00:11:32,726
As far as I know.

130
00:11:33,274 --> 00:11:37,318
RAY: Did you know
Babe Ruth copied his swing?

131
00:11:37,319 --> 00:11:42,319
If I did, I've forgotten it.

132
00:11:45,327 --> 00:11:48,872
He was supposed to be
so graceful and agile.

133
00:11:48,873 --> 00:11:51,875
I'd actually like
to see him play again,

134
00:11:51,876 --> 00:11:55,295
to let him play,
to right an old wrong.

135
00:11:55,296 --> 00:12:00,296
Wait. Wait a minute, Bosco.

136
00:12:00,342 --> 00:12:03,887
Are you actually thinking
of doing this?

137
00:12:03,888 --> 00:12:06,139
No.

138
00:12:06,140 --> 00:12:11,140
I mean, I can't think of one
good reason why I should, but...

139
00:12:18,194 --> 00:12:21,821
I'm 36. I have a wife,
a child, and a mortgage,

140
00:12:21,822 --> 00:12:26,242
and I'm scared to death
I'm turning into my father.

141
00:12:26,243 --> 00:12:30,246
What's your father got
to do with all of this?

142
00:12:30,247 --> 00:12:35,247
I never forgave him
for getting old.

143
00:12:35,794 --> 00:12:40,794
By the time he was as old
as I am now, he was ancient.

144
00:12:43,010 --> 00:12:48,010
I mean, he must have had dreams, but
he never did anything about them.

145
00:12:49,642 --> 00:12:52,435
For all I know, he may have
even heard voices, too,

146
00:12:52,436 --> 00:12:56,814
but he sure didn't listen
to them.

147
00:12:56,815 --> 00:13:01,815
The man never did one spontaneous
thing in all the years I knew him.

148
00:13:02,488 --> 00:13:07,116
Annie, I'm afraid
of that happening to me,

149
00:13:07,117 --> 00:13:12,117
and something tells me this may be my
last chance to do something about it.

150
00:13:15,209 --> 00:13:19,712
I want to build that field.

151
00:13:19,713 --> 00:13:22,131
Do you think I'm crazy?

152
00:13:22,132 --> 00:13:22,632
Yes.

153
00:13:28,013 --> 00:13:33,013
But I also think if you really
feel you should do this,

154
00:13:35,020 --> 00:13:40,020
then you should do it.

155
00:13:51,495 --> 00:13:53,705
What the hell is he doing?

156
00:13:53,706 --> 00:13:55,957
He's plowing under his corn.

157
00:13:55,958 --> 00:13:56,458
Why?

158
00:14:03,215 --> 00:14:06,926
Ty Cobb called him the greatest
left fielder of all time.

159
00:14:06,927 --> 00:14:11,639
He said his glove was the place
where triples go to die.

160
00:14:11,640 --> 00:14:13,599
<i>KAR/N: Could he hit?
RA Y: Could he hit?</i>

161
00:14:13,600 --> 00:14:16,894
<i>Lifetime average .356,
third highest in history.</i>

162
00:14:16,895 --> 00:14:19,397
<i>KAR/N: Why'd they call him
Shoeless Joe?</i>

163
00:14:19,398 --> 00:14:20,982
<i>RA Y: When he was still
in the minors,</i>

164
00:14:20,983 --> 00:14:23,901
<i>he bought a new pair of spikes
and hurt his feet.</i>

165
00:14:23,902 --> 00:14:27,864
<i>In the sixth inning, he took them
off and played in his socks.</i>

166
00:14:27,865 --> 00:14:29,282
<i>The players kidded him,</i>

167
00:14:29,283 --> 00:14:33,161
<i>called him "Shoeless Joe,"
and the name stuck.</i>

168
00:14:33,162 --> 00:14:34,787
MAN: He's going
to lose his farm.

169
00:14:34,788 --> 00:14:36,331
WOMAN: Damned fool.

170
00:14:36,332 --> 00:14:39,584
<i>RAY: Then in 1919, his team,
the Chicago White Sox,</i>

171
00:14:39,585 --> 00:14:42,045
<i>they threw the World Series.</i>

172
00:14:42,046 --> 00:14:43,421
<i>KAR/N: What's "threw"?</i>

173
00:14:43,422 --> 00:14:45,673
<i>RA Y: Lt means
they lost on purpose.</i>

174
00:14:45,674 --> 00:14:50,303
<i>Gamblers paid them to.
Except Shoeless Joe.</i>

175
00:14:50,304 --> 00:14:51,763
<i>He did take their money,</i>

176
00:14:51,764 --> 00:14:56,764
<i>but nobody ever proved he did
one thing to lose those games.</i>

177
00:14:57,144 --> 00:14:58,686
If he threw it,

178
00:14:58,687 --> 00:15:03,232
how do you explain he hit .375 for
the Series and committed no errors?

179
00:15:03,233 --> 00:15:04,442
I can't.

180
00:15:04,443 --> 00:15:07,195
Twelve hits including
the Series' only home run,

181
00:15:07,196 --> 00:15:09,447
and they said
he's trying to lose?

182
00:15:09,448 --> 00:15:11,366
It's ridiculous.

183
00:15:11,367 --> 00:15:14,285
<i>RA Y: The commissioner of baseball
suspended eight of the players,</i>

184
00:15:14,286 --> 00:15:17,580
<i>including the great Shoeless
Joe Jackson, for life.</i>

185
00:15:17,581 --> 00:15:20,375
<i>KAR/N: What's "suspend"?</i>

186
00:15:20,376 --> 00:15:25,376
<i>RA Y: Lt means they never
let him play the game again.</i>

187
00:15:26,256 --> 00:15:28,383
My father said
he saw him years later

188
00:15:28,384 --> 00:15:32,970
playing under a made-up name in
some 10th-rate league in Carolina.

189
00:15:32,971 --> 00:15:36,391
He'd put on 50 pounds, and his
spring was gone from his step

190
00:15:36,392 --> 00:15:39,310
but he could still hit.

191
00:15:39,311 --> 00:15:44,232
Dad used to say nobody could
hit like Shoeless Joe.

192
00:15:44,233 --> 00:15:46,859
I think that's the first time
I've ever seen you smile

193
00:15:46,860 --> 00:15:51,860
when you mentioned your father.

194
00:15:53,617 --> 00:15:54,117
Well...

195
00:16:03,335 --> 00:16:08,335
I have just created something
totally illogical.

196
00:16:10,259 --> 00:16:15,012
That's what I like about it.

197
00:16:15,013 --> 00:16:19,600
Am I completely nuts?

198
00:16:19,601 --> 00:16:22,353
Not completely.

199
00:16:22,354 --> 00:16:25,815
It's a good baseball field,
Ray.

200
00:16:25,816 --> 00:16:27,859
It's kind of pretty, isn't it?

201
00:16:27,860 --> 00:16:28,404
Mmm-hmm.

202
00:16:51,216 --> 00:16:55,553
Any sign?

203
00:16:55,554 --> 00:16:58,723
Something's going to happen
out there.

204
00:16:58,724 --> 00:17:03,724
I can feel it.

205
00:17:20,329 --> 00:17:23,873
<i>ANNOUNCER ON TV: So, for the veteran
southpaw, his summer of woes continues.</i>

206
00:17:23,874 --> 00:17:26,000
<i>That's four straight hits
in the inning.</i>

207
00:17:26,001 --> 00:17:31,001
Daddy, what's a "southpaw"?

208
00:17:31,632 --> 00:17:35,635
It means
a left-handed pitcher, honey.

209
00:17:35,636 --> 00:17:37,845
So how bad is it?

210
00:17:37,846 --> 00:17:42,350
Well, considering how much
less acreage we have for corn,

211
00:17:42,351 --> 00:17:45,269
I say we'll probably

212
00:17:45,270 --> 00:17:50,270
almost break even.

213
00:17:51,360 --> 00:17:54,737
We used up all our savings
on that field, Ray.

214
00:17:54,738 --> 00:17:55,947
Daddy?

215
00:17:55,948 --> 00:18:00,948
Justa minute, Karin.

216
00:18:02,120 --> 00:18:07,120
So what are you saying?
We can't keep the field?

217
00:18:07,960 --> 00:18:12,960
Makes it real hard
to keep the farm.

218
00:18:15,259 --> 00:18:16,300
Daddy.

219
00:18:16,301 --> 00:18:18,761
In a minute, Karin!

220
00:18:18,762 --> 00:18:23,762
There's a man out there
on your lawn.

221
00:19:08,520 --> 00:19:13,520
I'll put up some coffee.
Why don't you go on outside?

222
00:21:10,308 --> 00:21:10,808
Sorry.

223
00:21:15,021 --> 00:21:20,021
I'll get some out there.

224
00:21:47,971 --> 00:21:51,015
Hi.

225
00:21:51,016 --> 00:21:54,351
Ray Kinsella.

226
00:21:54,352 --> 00:21:59,352
Joe Jackson.

227
00:22:23,965 --> 00:22:28,965
I bet it's good
to be playing again, huh?

228
00:22:34,017 --> 00:22:37,770
Getting thrown out of baseball

229
00:22:37,771 --> 00:22:42,650
was like having
part of me amputated.

230
00:22:42,651 --> 00:22:43,984
I've heard that old men wake up

231
00:22:43,985 --> 00:22:48,985
and scratch itchy legs that have
been dust for over 50 years.

232
00:22:50,033 --> 00:22:53,118
That was me.

233
00:22:53,119 --> 00:22:56,330
I'd wake up at night

234
00:22:56,331 --> 00:23:00,042
with the smell of the ballpark
in my nose,

235
00:23:00,043 --> 00:23:05,043
with the cool of the grass
on my feet,

236
00:23:05,465 --> 00:23:10,465
the thrill of the grass.

237
00:23:15,475 --> 00:23:18,477
Can you pitch?

