00:41:04,293 --> 00:41:06,461
In the April 1962 issue
of Jet Magazine,

492
00:41:06,462 --> 00:41:09,631
there's a story called
"This Is Not A Kite."

493
00:41:09,632 --> 00:41:11,466
It's not his best work,

494
00:41:11,467 --> 00:41:14,844
but the story's hero

495
00:41:14,845 --> 00:41:17,263
is named John Kinsella,
my father.

496
00:41:17,264 --> 00:41:18,431
Wow.

497
00:41:18,432 --> 00:41:20,183
What do you mean, "Wow"?

498
00:41:20,184 --> 00:41:24,354
Big wow! What's it got to do
with baseball?

499
00:41:24,355 --> 00:41:29,355
You drive.

500
00:41:30,986 --> 00:41:34,197
Okay, the last interview
he ever gave was in 1973.

501
00:41:34,198 --> 00:41:35,531
Guess what it's about.

502
00:41:35,532 --> 00:41:37,158
Some kind of team sport.

503
00:41:37,159 --> 00:41:40,328
Mann was a baseball fanatic.
Listen to this.

504
00:41:40,329 --> 00:41:44,123
"My earliest recurring dream
was to play at Ebbets Field"

505
00:41:44,124 --> 00:41:46,584
"with Jackie Robinson
and the Brooklyn Dodgers."

506
00:41:46,585 --> 00:41:49,212
Wtneverhappened.
The Dodgers left Brooklyn.

507
00:41:49,213 --> 00:41:54,050
"Ebbets Field is gone,
but I still dream that dream."

508
00:41:54,051 --> 00:41:57,887
That's sad.

509
00:41:57,888 --> 00:42:01,724
RAY: The man wrote the best
books of his generation.

510
00:42:01,725 --> 00:42:05,478
He was a pioneer in the civil
rights and the antiwar movement.

511
00:42:05,479 --> 00:42:07,605
I mean, he made
the cover of Newsweek.

512
00:42:07,606 --> 00:42:11,693
He knew everybody. He did everything.
He helped shape his time.

513
00:42:11,694 --> 00:42:13,987
The guy hung out
with the Beatles.

514
00:42:13,988 --> 00:42:17,073
It wasn't enough.
What he missed was baseball.

515
00:42:17,074 --> 00:42:18,741
Oh, my God! What?

516
00:42:18,742 --> 00:42:21,911
"As a small boy,
he had a bat named Rosebud."

517
00:42:21,912 --> 00:42:24,080
Give me that. Sorry.

518
00:42:24,081 --> 00:42:28,334
The guy hasn't been
to a baseball game since 1958.

519
00:42:28,335 --> 00:42:32,171
So, in order to ease his pain, you're
supposed to take him to a ballgame.

520
00:42:32,172 --> 00:42:34,632
Yes.

521
00:42:34,633 --> 00:42:37,468
Ray, this is nuttier than
building the baseball field.

522
00:42:37,469 --> 00:42:38,761
No. No, it's not.

523
00:42:38,762 --> 00:42:42,849
It's pretty weird, but building
the field was 5, 10% weirder.

524
00:42:42,850 --> 00:42:45,643
I'm going to have
to nip this one in the bud.

525
00:42:45,644 --> 00:42:49,063
We're having moderate-to-heavy
financial difficulties here.

526
00:42:49,064 --> 00:42:52,442
And you can't take off for Boston
while we're going broke in Iowa.

527
00:42:52,443 --> 00:42:54,777
This is really
new territory for us,

528
00:42:54,778 --> 00:42:57,447
but we're dealing
with primal forces of nature.

529
00:42:57,448 --> 00:43:01,617
The prudent thing is not
to quibble over details.

530
00:43:01,618 --> 00:43:06,122
Yeah, but why do you have to go? Why
can't the voice send somebody else?

531
00:43:06,123 --> 00:43:09,250
How about Shirley MacLaine?
Is she too busy?

532
00:43:09,251 --> 00:43:11,335
What does this have
to do with you?

533
00:43:11,336 --> 00:43:13,629
RAY: That's what I have
to find out.

534
00:43:13,630 --> 00:43:17,800
Ray, we are behind on the mortgage.
That field ate up all of our savings.

535
00:43:17,801 --> 00:43:19,385
We could lose this farm.

536
00:43:19,386 --> 00:43:23,097
I won't even stay in motels. I'll
sleep in the car. I'll beg for food.

537
00:43:23,098 --> 00:43:27,769
No. No! Now, this is too much!

538
00:43:27,770 --> 00:43:31,898
Now, look. I understand your need to
prove to yourself and to the world

539
00:43:31,899 --> 00:43:34,400
you are not turning into your
father, but you've done it.

540
00:43:34,401 --> 00:43:37,820
You believed in the magic. Ithappened.
Isn't that enough?

541
00:43:37,821 --> 00:43:41,449
It's more than that.
I know this is totally nuts,

542
00:43:41,450 --> 00:43:43,826
but there's another reason
I'm supposed to do it.

543
00:43:43,827 --> 00:43:47,163
I feel it as strongly
as I've felt anything.

544
00:43:47,164 --> 00:43:48,289
There's a reason.

545
00:43:48,290 --> 00:43:51,000
What? Just tell me what it is.

546
00:43:51,001 --> 00:43:52,835
Something's going to happen
at the game.

547
00:43:52,836 --> 00:43:55,254
There's something
at Fenway Park.

548
00:43:55,255 --> 00:43:59,634
I got to be there with
Terence Mann to find it out.

549
00:43:59,635 --> 00:44:04,180
Is Fenway the one with the big
green wall in left field?

550
00:44:04,181 --> 00:44:07,183
Yeah.

551
00:44:07,184 --> 00:44:11,604
I dreamt last night you were
at Fenway with Terence Mann.

552
00:44:11,605 --> 00:44:14,357
Was I sitting on the
first base side? Yes.

553
00:44:14,358 --> 00:44:16,234
About halfway up on the aisle?

554
00:44:16,235 --> 00:44:19,028
Yeah. Eating a hot dog.
Eating a hot dog.

555
00:44:19,029 --> 00:44:20,988
I had the same dream.

556
00:44:20,989 --> 00:44:25,989
I'll help you pack.

557
00:44:49,226 --> 00:44:50,810
RAY: Hi, I'm...

558
00:44:50,811 --> 00:44:52,728
Hi, I'm Ray Kinsella.

559
00:44:52,729 --> 00:44:54,397
Hi. No.

560
00:44:54,398 --> 00:44:55,815
Hi.

561
00:44:55,816 --> 00:44:59,277
Hi, I'm Ray Kinsella. It's a great
pleasure to finally get to...

562
00:44:59,278 --> 00:45:02,405
Hi, I'm Ray Kinsella.
I'm a big fan of yours.

563
00:45:02,406 --> 00:45:04,782
Hi.

564
00:45:04,783 --> 00:45:06,742
Hi.

565
00:45:06,743 --> 00:45:08,870
How do you do, Mr. Mann?

566
00:45:08,871 --> 00:45:12,248
I have to take you to a base...

567
00:45:12,249 --> 00:45:16,252
All right, stupid, put your
hands up and get in the trunk.

568
00:45:16,253 --> 00:45:20,089
Good. Good.

569
00:45:20,090 --> 00:45:23,885
He lives right around here.
Do you know him?

570
00:45:23,886 --> 00:45:27,597
He's sort of a tall black man.
I'm a friend of his.

571
00:45:27,598 --> 00:45:32,598
If he was much of a friend, he could
give you the directions himself.

572
00:45:34,771 --> 00:45:39,150
That's a good point. Thank you.

573
00:45:39,151 --> 00:45:42,737
I don't know where he lives.
Get away from me!

574
00:45:42,738 --> 00:45:45,239
I ain't going
to tell you nothing.

575
00:45:45,240 --> 00:45:50,240
Go away! You're a pest!

576
00:45:51,914 --> 00:45:54,123
Two blocks down,
right-hand side.

577
00:45:54,124 --> 00:45:57,752
First door that don't have a
chicken in the window is his.

578
00:45:57,753 --> 00:46:02,753
No chicken.

579
00:46:44,341 --> 00:46:49,341
Who the hell are you?

580
00:46:49,513 --> 00:46:54,513
Sir, my name's Ray Kinsella.

581
00:47:11,201 --> 00:47:12,868
We got
a learning disability here?

582
00:47:12,869 --> 00:47:14,787
If I could just have
one minute, please.

583
00:47:14,788 --> 00:47:17,957
Look, I can't tell you
the secret of life,

584
00:47:17,958 --> 00:47:20,543
and I don't have
any answers for you.

585
00:47:20,544 --> 00:47:24,046
I don't give interviews, and
I'm no longer a public figure.

586
00:47:24,047 --> 00:47:27,883
I just want to be left alone,
so piss off.

587
00:47:27,884 --> 00:47:30,553
Wait! Wait!

588
00:47:30,554 --> 00:47:32,847
Look, I've come 1,500 miles
to see you

589
00:47:32,848 --> 00:47:36,726
at the risk of losing my home
and alienating my wife.

590
00:47:36,727 --> 00:47:40,146
All I'm asking is one minute.

591
00:47:40,147 --> 00:47:40,647
Please.

592
00:47:45,193 --> 00:47:50,193
One minute.

593
00:47:55,871 --> 00:47:59,749
Okay, I understand
your desire for privacy,

594
00:47:59,750 --> 00:48:03,169
and lwouldn't dream of intruding if
this weren't extremely important.

595
00:48:03,170 --> 00:48:07,423
Oh, God.
I don't do causes anymore.

596
00:48:07,424 --> 00:48:09,258
This isn't a cause.

597
00:48:09,259 --> 00:48:11,510
I don't need money
or an endorsement.

598
00:48:11,511 --> 00:48:13,262
Refreshing.

599
00:48:13,263 --> 00:48:14,555
You once wrote,

600
00:48:14,556 --> 00:48:18,601
"There comes a time when all the cosmic
tumblers have clicked into place"

601
00:48:18,602 --> 00:48:21,270
"and the universe opens
itself up for a few seconds"

602
00:48:21,271 --> 00:48:24,023
"to show you what's possible."

603
00:48:24,024 --> 00:48:26,442
Oh, my God!

604
00:48:26,443 --> 00:48:27,526
What?

605
00:48:27,527 --> 00:48:29,195
You're from the '60s.

606
00:48:29,196 --> 00:48:31,822
Well, yeah. Actually...

607
00:48:31,823 --> 00:48:33,115
Out! Hey!

608
00:48:33,116 --> 00:48:34,825
Back to the '60s.

609
00:48:34,826 --> 00:48:39,826
No place for you here in the future.
Get back while you still can!

610
00:48:41,625 --> 00:48:44,335
You've changed, you know that?

611
00:48:44,336 --> 00:48:46,253
Yes, I suppose I have.

612
00:48:46,254 --> 00:48:51,254
How about this? Peace, love, dope.
Now get the hell out of here!

613
00:49:34,386 --> 00:49:37,680
You've really pissed me off.

614
00:49:37,681 --> 00:49:39,807
Hold it.

615
00:49:39,808 --> 00:49:41,684
I was hoping I wouldn't have
to do it this way.

616
00:49:41,685 --> 00:49:43,686
What the hell is that?

617
00:49:43,687 --> 00:49:45,354
It's a gun.

618
00:49:45,355 --> 00:49:46,605
It's your finger.

619
00:49:46,606 --> 00:49:48,023
No, it's a gun.

620
00:49:48,024 --> 00:49:49,525
Let me see it.

621
00:49:49,526 --> 00:49:51,902
I'm not going to show you
my gun.

622
00:49:51,903 --> 00:49:56,903
I'm not going to hurt you.
I need you to come with...

623
00:49:57,033 --> 00:49:58,534
What are you doing?

624
00:49:58,535 --> 00:50:01,203
I'll beat you with a crowbar
until you go away.

625
00:50:01,204 --> 00:50:03,622
Whoa! Wait! You can't do that.

626
00:50:03,623 --> 00:50:07,918
There are rules here? Oh, no.
There are no rules here.

627
00:50:07,919 --> 00:50:12,919
You're a pacifist!

628
00:50:14,885 --> 00:50:16,385
Shit.

629
00:50:16,386 --> 00:50:20,097
Thank you. Thank you.

630
00:50:20,098 --> 00:50:24,393
So what? You kidnapping me?
What's the deal here?

631
00:50:24,394 --> 00:50:27,813
I was...

632
00:50:27,814 --> 00:50:30,733
I was hoping I could just
convince you to come with me.

633
00:50:30,734 --> 00:50:33,569
So you are kidnapping me?

634
00:50:33,570 --> 00:50:37,072
I have to take you
to a baseball game.

635
00:50:37,073 --> 00:50:38,866
You what?

636
00:50:38,867 --> 00:50:41,535
Tonight's game. Red Sox, A's.

637
00:50:41,536 --> 00:50:44,497
Why?

638
00:50:44,498 --> 00:50:45,915
Something will happen there.

639
00:50:45,916 --> 00:50:50,916
I don't know what, but we'll
find out when it does.

640
00:50:51,922 --> 00:50:53,255
My name's Ray Kinsella.

641
00:50:53,256 --> 00:50:57,218
You used my father's name for a
character in one of your stories.

642
00:50:57,219 --> 00:50:58,844
John Kinsella.

643
00:50:58,845 --> 00:51:01,639
You're seeing a whole team
of psychiatrists, aren't you?

644
00:51:01,640 --> 00:51:06,640
I don't blame you for thinking
that, but, no, I'm not.

645
00:51:07,187 --> 00:51:11,023
I swear to God, I'm the least
crazy person I've ever known.

646
00:51:11,024 --> 00:51:15,319
Why are you kidnapping me
to a baseball game?

647
00:51:15,320 --> 00:51:16,612
Mayl...

648
00:51:16,613 --> 00:51:18,489
Oh, please.

649
00:51:18,490 --> 00:51:20,074
Want a cup of coffee?

650
00:51:20,075 --> 00:51:21,992
No.

651
00:51:21,993 --> 00:51:24,912
Want some cookies?

652
00:51:24,913 --> 00:51:28,082
No.

653
00:51:28,083 --> 00:51:30,709
I read an interview you gave
a long time ago

654
00:51:30,710 --> 00:51:33,254
about how you always dreamed
of playing at Ebbets Field

655
00:51:33,255 --> 00:51:36,257
and how sad you felt
when they tore it down.

656
00:51:36,258 --> 00:51:38,926
I never said that.

657
00:51:38,927 --> 00:51:40,135
You didn't?

658
00:51:40,136 --> 00:51:45,136
I don't even recall
thinking that.

659
00:51:46,059 --> 00:51:51,059
This is so weird.

660
00:51:51,356 --> 00:51:54,316
This whole...

661
00:51:54,317 --> 00:51:58,612
This whole thing is so weird.

662
00:51:58,613 --> 00:52:03,613
Then why go through with it?

663
00:52:03,868 --> 00:52:08,868
It's a long story.

664
00:52:10,333 --> 00:52:12,501
But it's a really good story.

665
00:52:12,502 --> 00:52:14,670
I'll tell you on the way.

666
00:52:14,671 --> 00:52:17,006
I'm not going to get rid
of you, am I?

667
00:52:17,007 --> 00:52:22,007
Come to this game. I'll never
bother you again, noteven_.

668
00:52:22,095 --> 00:52:27,095
Not even a Christmas card.

669
00:52:31,354 --> 00:52:33,105
<i>(ANNOUNCER SPEAKING ON PA)</i>

670
00:52:33,106 --> 00:52:35,232
So what do you do
with yourself these days?

671
00:52:35,233 --> 00:52:37,526
I live, I work.

672
00:52:37,527 --> 00:52:39,528
I learned how to cook.

673
00:52:39,529 --> 00:52:43,616
I take walks and watch sunsets.

674
00:52:43,617 --> 00:52:46,035
Don't you miss being involved?

675
00:52:46,036 --> 00:52:49,663
I was the East Coast
distributor of involved.

676
00:52:49,664 --> 00:52:52,541
Late it and drank it
and breathed it.

677
00:52:52,542 --> 00:52:56,086
Then they killed
Martin and Bobby,

678
00:52:56,087 --> 00:52:58,547
they elected Tricky Dick twice,

679
00:52:58,548 --> 00:53:00,382
and now people like you think

680
00:53:00,383 --> 00:53:02,593
I must be miserable because
I'm not involved anymore.

681
00:53:02,594 --> 00:53:04,970
I've got news for you.

682
00:53:04,971 --> 00:53:07,640
I spent all my misery
years ago.

683
00:53:07,641 --> 00:53:09,892
I have no more pain left
for any of you.

684
00:53:09,893 --> 00:53:13,020
I gave at the office.

685
00:53:13,021 --> 00:53:15,606
So what do you want?

686
00:53:15,607 --> 00:53:18,359
I want them to stop
looking to me for answers,

687
00:53:18,360 --> 00:53:21,695
begging me to speak again,
write again, be a leader.

688
00:53:21,696 --> 00:53:24,198
I want them to start thinking
for themselves.

689
00:53:24,199 --> 00:53:27,326
I want my privacy.

690
00:53:27,327 --> 00:53:32,327
No, I meant what do you want?

691
00:53:35,001 --> 00:53:37,419
Oh.

692
00:53:37,420 --> 00:53:41,090
Dog and a beer.

693
00:53:41,091 --> 00:53:42,549
Two.

694
00:53:42,550 --> 00:53:44,677
10 bucks.

695
00:53:44,678 --> 00:53:46,595
Okay, I understand.

696
00:53:46,596 --> 00:53:49,098
You should be entitled to
as much privacy as you want,

697
00:53:49,099 --> 00:53:52,017
but why stop writing?

698
00:53:52,018 --> 00:53:54,186
I haven't published a word
in 17 years,

699
00:53:54,187 --> 00:53:57,106
and still I have to endure
lunatics like you.

700
00:53:57,107 --> 00:54:00,984
What do you think would happen if I
suddenly came out with a new book?

701
00:54:00,985 --> 00:54:05,985
They'd bleed me dry.

702
00:54:16,960 --> 00:54:21,960
<i>MALE VO/CE: Go the distance.</i>

703
00:54:27,387 --> 00:54:32,387
<i>Go the distance.</i>

704
00:54:49,534 --> 00:54:54,534
What's the matter?

705
00:54:54,664 --> 00:54:56,498
You didn't see that?

706
00:54:56,499 --> 00:54:57,111
See what?

707
00:55:04,549 --> 00:55:06,884
I'm sorry. I guess
you didn't have to be here.

708
00:55:06,885 --> 00:55:07,385
What?

709
00:55:11,347 --> 00:55:14,558
Whenever you want to go,
we can go.

710
00:55:14,559 --> 00:55:19,559
Fine. Let's go.

711
00:56:02,607 --> 00:56:06,068
What is it
you're not telling me?

712
00:56:06,069 --> 00:56:11,069
I've already taken up
too much of your time.

713
00:56:21,125 --> 00:56:23,627
I wish I had your passion, Ray.

714
00:56:23,628 --> 00:56:27,297
Misdirected though it might
be, it is still a passion.

715
00:56:27,298 --> 00:56:32,298
I used to feel that way
about things, but...

716
00:56:33,596 --> 00:56:35,848
You got another message,
didn't you?

717
00:56:35,849 --> 00:56:37,307
You'll think I'm crazy.

718
00:56:37,308 --> 00:56:39,268
I already think you're crazy.

719
00:56:39,269 --> 00:56:43,772
What did it say?

720
00:56:43,773 --> 00:56:48,773
It said, "The man's done enough.
Leave him alone."

721
00:57:07,547 --> 00:57:10,173
"Moonlight" Graham.

722
00:57:10,174 --> 00:57:11,466
You saw it.

723
00:57:11,467 --> 00:57:13,427
Saw what?

724
00:57:13,428 --> 00:57:16,513
You saw it.
New York Giants, 1922.

725
00:57:16,514 --> 00:57:19,057
He played one game.
He never got to bat.

726
00:57:19,058 --> 00:57:22,060
What did I see?
Chisholm, Minnesota.

727
00:57:22,061 --> 00:57:25,772
We were the only ones who saw it.
Did you hear the voice, too?

728
00:57:25,773 --> 00:57:30,773
It's what told me to find you.
Did you hear it?

729
00:57:32,030 --> 00:57:34,781
"Go the distance"?

730
00:57:34,782 --> 00:57:37,743
Yes. Do you know what it means?

731
00:57:37,744 --> 00:57:38,994
Yes.

732
00:57:38,995 --> 00:57:40,245
What?

733
00:57:40,246 --> 00:57:43,457
It means we're going to Minnesota
to find "Moonlight" Graham.

734
00:57:43,458 --> 00:57:45,167
We're going... We?

735
00:57:45,168 --> 00:57:46,919
I must be out of my mind.

736
00:57:46,920 --> 00:57:49,338
What do we do when we find him?

737
00:57:49,339 --> 00:57:51,798
How the hell
am I supposed to know?

738
00:57:51,799 --> 00:57:55,302
That's right.
You're right. You're right.

739
00:57:55,303 --> 00:57:56,845
This is so bitching.

740
00:57:56,846 --> 00:58:01,846
I don't believe I'm doing this.

741
00:58:16,866 --> 00:58:20,118
<i>RA Y: Hey, Annie, guess what?
I'm with Terence Mann.</i>

742
00:58:20,119 --> 00:58:22,287
<i>ANN/E: Oh, my God.
You kidnapped him.</i>

743
00:58:22,288 --> 00:58:25,082
<i>No, I didn't. He wanted to.</i>

744
00:58:25,083 --> 00:58:28,460
<i>Sorry, but I'm going
to be a few days longer.</i>

745
00:58:28,461 --> 00:58:31,129
<i>We're going to Minnesota.
ANN/E: I don't believe this.</i>

746
00:58:31,130 --> 00:58:32,839
<i>What's in Minnesota?</i>

747
00:58:32,840 --> 00:58:35,717
An old ballplayer.
I'll explain when I get home.

748
00:58:35,718 --> 00:58:37,678
How are things with you?

749
00:58:37,679 --> 00:58:39,012
<i>ANN/E.' Fine.</i>

750
00:58:39,013 --> 00:58:42,349
Great. Look, Ann,
I got to go, okay?

751
00:58:42,350 --> 00:58:44,851
Give Karin a hug for me,

752
00:58:44,852 --> 00:58:46,395
and I love you.

753
00:58:46,396 --> 00:58:47,729
I love you, too.

754
00:58:47,730 --> 00:58:51,066
Hey, someday explain all this
to me, okay?

755
00:58:51,067 --> 00:58:52,609
I'll try.

756
00:58:52,610 --> 00:58:53,819
Bye-bye.

757
00:58:53,820 --> 00:58:54,320
Bye.

758
00:59:02,120 --> 00:59:06,373
Why didn't you tell him?

759
00:59:06,374 --> 00:59:11,374
Annie, you got no choice
in the matter.

760
00:59:13,881 --> 00:59:15,799
RAY: Half a dozen Grahams.

761
00:59:15,800 --> 00:59:20,262
No Archibald. No "Moonlight."

762
00:59:20,263 --> 00:59:25,263
Follow me.

763
00:59:33,651 --> 00:59:36,361
Hello.

764
00:59:36,362 --> 00:59:38,363
Excuse me.
Maybe you can help us.

765
00:59:38,364 --> 00:59:41,783
We're looking for an ex-baseball
player named Archibald Graham.

766
00:59:41,784 --> 00:59:43,201
Oh, you mean Doc Graham.

767
00:59:43,202 --> 00:59:45,787
No. I think
his nickname was "Moonlight."

768
00:59:45,788 --> 00:59:47,205
Well, that's Dr. Graham.

769
00:59:47,206 --> 00:59:48,790
Dr. Graham?

770
00:59:48,791 --> 00:59:51,126
His baseball career
never amounted to much.

771
00:59:51,127 --> 00:59:53,253
He went back to school.

772
00:59:53,254 --> 00:59:54,755
His father was a doctor.

773
00:59:54,756 --> 00:59:56,298
Do you know
where we can find him?

774
00:59:56,299 --> 01:00:00,719
It's nothing bad.
We're not from the IRS.

775
01:00:00,720 --> 01:00:02,637
Doc Graham is dead.

776
01:00:02,638 --> 01:00:07,638
He died in 1972.

777
01:00:07,685 --> 01:00:09,811
"And there were times
when children could not afford"

778
01:00:09,812 --> 01:00:12,647
"eyeglasses or milk
or clothing."

779
01:00:12,648 --> 01:00:15,650
"Yet, no child was ever denied
these essentials"

780
01:00:15,651 --> 01:00:19,071
"because, in the background,
there was always Dr. Graham."

781
01:00:19,072 --> 01:00:21,490
"Without any fanfare
or publicity,"

782
01:00:21,491 --> 01:00:25,327
"the glasses or the milk
or the ticket to the ballgame"

783
01:00:25,328 --> 01:00:28,747
"found their way
into the child's pocket."

784
01:00:28,748 --> 01:00:30,999
You wrote that.

785
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:32,292
The day he died.

786
01:00:32,293 --> 01:00:33,794
Can I see that?

787
01:00:33,795 --> 01:00:35,545
You're a good writer.

788
01:00:35,546 --> 01:00:37,005
So are you.

789
01:00:37,006 --> 01:00:42,006
(PHONE RINGING)

790
01:00:43,012 --> 01:00:46,556
Something's missing.

791
01:00:46,557 --> 01:00:50,602
Well, he sounds like
he was a wonderful man.

792
01:00:50,603 --> 01:00:54,481
Half the towns in North
America have a Doc Graham.

793
01:00:54,482 --> 01:00:58,360
What makes this one so special we
travel across the country to find him

794
01:00:58,361 --> 01:01:01,363
16 years after he died?

795
01:01:01,364 --> 01:01:06,364
There's got to be more.

796
01:01:09,330 --> 01:01:10,956
What else?

797
01:01:10,957 --> 01:01:13,500
He always wore an overcoat,

798
01:01:13,501 --> 01:01:15,377
he had white hair,

799
01:01:15,378 --> 01:01:17,504
and he always carried
an umbrella.

800
01:01:17,505 --> 01:01:19,047
What was the umbrella for?

801
01:01:19,048 --> 01:01:22,634
It got to be a habit,
something to hang on to.

802
01:01:22,635 --> 01:01:27,055
He said he used it to beat
away his lady admirers.

803
01:01:27,056 --> 01:01:29,224
Tell me about his wife.

804
01:01:29,225 --> 01:01:31,893
Alicia.

805
01:01:31,894 --> 01:01:36,894
She moved to South Carolina
after Doc passed.

806
01:01:37,400 --> 01:01:40,527
She passed
a couple years later.

807
01:01:40,528 --> 01:01:43,864
She always wore blue.

808
01:01:43,865 --> 01:01:48,577
The shopkeepers in town
would stock blue hats

809
01:01:48,578 --> 01:01:53,578
because they knew if Doc
walked by, he'd buy one.

810
01:01:55,293 --> 01:01:58,086
When they cleaned out
his office,

811
01:01:58,087 --> 01:02:02,674
they found boxes of blue hats

812
01:02:02,675 --> 01:02:06,052
that he never got around
to give her.

813
01:02:06,053 --> 01:02:08,555
I'll bet you didn't know that.

814
01:02:08,556 --> 01:02:13,556
No, I didn't.

815
01:02:13,603 --> 01:02:18,603
No screwing, no drinking, no
opium, no midnight abortions,

816
01:02:19,567 --> 01:02:21,943
no illegitimate children,

817
01:02:21,944 --> 01:02:23,987
no shady finances.

818
01:02:23,988 --> 01:02:27,157
You sound disappointed.

819
01:02:27,158 --> 01:02:31,036
Shoeless Joe had a problem.
That's why he needed you.

820
01:02:31,037 --> 01:02:32,829
This guy doesn't need us.

821
01:02:32,830 --> 01:02:37,042
Terence.

822
01:02:37,043 --> 01:02:42,043
Do you know you're missing?

823
01:02:43,633 --> 01:02:46,301
Oh, God.

824
01:02:46,302 --> 01:02:48,720
"His father,
who lives in Baltimore,"

825
01:02:48,721 --> 01:02:52,682
"notified police after receiving no
answer to repeated telephone calls."

826
01:02:52,683 --> 01:02:54,809
Shoot

827
01:02:54,810 --> 01:02:56,436
I better call him.

828
01:02:56,437 --> 01:02:58,188
You want me to...

829
01:02:58,189 --> 01:02:58,689
Thanks.

830
01:03:05,821 --> 01:03:10,821
I'm taking a walk.
Be back in a while.

831
01:03:14,330 --> 01:03:19,330
What do I tell him?

832
01:03:43,985 --> 01:03:48,985
"This year's"?

833
01:04:27,111 --> 01:04:32,111
Dr. Graham?

834
01:04:37,496 --> 01:04:42,496
Dr. Graham?

835
01:04:43,252 --> 01:04:48,252
My name's Ray Kinsella.
I'm from Iowa.

836
01:04:49,216 --> 01:04:54,216
Are you "Moonlight" Graham?

837
01:04:56,015 --> 01:05:01,015
No one's called me "Moonlight"
Graham in 50 years.

838
01:05:01,896 --> 01:05:04,314
Well, I've come
a very long way to see you.

839
01:05:04,315 --> 01:05:07,859
I couldn't sleep tonight.
Usually I sleep like a baby.

840
01:05:07,860 --> 01:05:12,530
I told Alicia
I was taking a walk.

841
01:05:12,531 --> 01:05:14,783
Do you mind if I join you?

842
01:05:14,784 --> 01:05:17,327
I'd like to talk to you.

843
01:05:17,328 --> 01:05:21,331
Let's walk over to my office.

844
01:05:21,332 --> 01:05:23,541
What do you want
to talk to me about?

845
01:05:23,542 --> 01:05:27,545
When you got to the majors, you
played only one inning of one game.

846
01:05:27,546 --> 01:05:30,507
What happened that inning?

847
01:05:30,508 --> 01:05:32,884
GRAHAM: It was the last day
of the season,

848
01:05:32,885 --> 01:05:35,428
bottom of the eighth,
we were way ahead.

849
01:05:35,429 --> 01:05:39,808
In three weeks,
I hadn't seen any action.

850
01:05:39,809 --> 01:05:43,269
Suddenly old John McGraw points
a bony finger in my direction

851
01:05:43,270 --> 01:05:46,439
and he says, "Right field."

852
01:05:46,440 --> 01:05:49,109
Ijumped up like I was sitting
on a spring,

853
01:05:49,110 --> 01:05:54,110
grabbed my glove,
and ran out on the field.

854
01:05:55,699 --> 01:05:58,034
RAY: Did you get to make
a play?

855
01:05:58,035 --> 01:06:02,455
They never hit the ball
out of the infield.

856
01:06:02,456 --> 01:06:05,792
The game ended.
The season was over.

857
01:06:05,793 --> 01:06:08,670
I knew they'd send me
back down.

858
01:06:08,671 --> 01:06:12,090
I couldn't bear the thought
of another year in the minors.

859
01:06:12,091 --> 01:06:17,091
So I decided to hang them up.

860
01:06:17,555 --> 01:06:18,805
Go on. Sit down.

861
01:06:18,806 --> 01:06:22,517
Thank you.

862
01:06:22,518 --> 01:06:26,521
So what was that like?

863
01:06:26,522 --> 01:06:29,983
Itwas like coming
this close to your dreams,

864
01:06:29,984 --> 01:06:34,070
then watch them brush past you,
like a stranger in a crowd.

865
01:06:34,071 --> 01:06:35,989
Then, you don't think about it.

866
01:06:35,990 --> 01:06:38,867
We just don't recognize life's
most significant moments

867
01:06:38,868 --> 01:06:40,076
while they're happening.

868
01:06:40,077 --> 01:06:43,872
Back then I thought, "Well,
there'll be other days."

869
01:06:43,873 --> 01:06:48,626
I didn't realize that
that was the only day.

870
01:06:48,627 --> 01:06:52,755
And now,
I want to ask you a question.

871
01:06:52,756 --> 01:06:57,218
What's so interesting about half an
inning that you'd come from Iowa

872
01:06:57,219 --> 01:07:01,806
to talk to me about it
50 years after it happened?

873
01:07:01,807 --> 01:07:05,351
I didn't really know
till just now,

874
01:07:05,352 --> 01:07:09,647
but I think it's to ask you if you
could do anything you wanted,

875
01:07:09,648 --> 01:07:14,648
if you could have a wish...

876
01:07:15,863 --> 01:07:20,533
And you're the kind of a man
who could grant me that wish?

877
01:07:20,534 --> 01:07:24,746
I don't know. I'm just asking.

878
01:07:24,747 --> 01:07:27,081
Well, you know,

879
01:07:27,082 --> 01:07:29,375
I never got to bat
in the major leagues.

880
01:07:29,376 --> 01:07:32,587
I'd have liked to have had
that chance, just once,

881
01:07:32,588 --> 01:07:34,923
to stare down
a big-league pitcher.

882
01:07:34,924 --> 01:07:39,677
Then just as he goes
into his windup, wink.

883
01:07:39,678 --> 01:07:42,305
Make him think
you know something he doesn't.

884
01:07:42,306 --> 01:07:44,307
That's what I wish for.

885
01:07:44,308 --> 01:07:48,353
The chance to squint at a sky so blue
it hurts your eyes to look at it,

886
01:07:48,354 --> 01:07:51,272
to feel the tingle in your arms
as you connect with the ball,

887
01:07:51,273 --> 01:07:56,273
run bases, stretching a double into a
triple and flop face first into third,

888
01:07:56,612 --> 01:07:59,364
wrap your arms around the bag.

889
01:07:59,365 --> 01:08:04,285
That's my wish. That's my wish.

890
01:08:04,286 --> 01:08:07,288
Is there enough magic
out there in the moonlight

891
01:08:07,289 --> 01:08:09,874
to make this dream come true?

892
01:08:09,875 --> 01:08:13,795
What would you say
if I said yes?

893
01:08:13,796 --> 01:08:17,549
I think
I'd actually believe you.

894
01:08:17,550 --> 01:08:20,051
There's a place where
things like that happen.

895
01:08:20,052 --> 01:08:25,052
If you want to go,
I can take you.

896
01:08:27,351 --> 01:08:30,979
This is my most special place
in all the world.

897
01:08:30,980 --> 01:08:35,980
Once a place touches you like this,
the wind never blows so cold again.

898
01:08:36,485 --> 01:08:41,485
You feel for it,
like it was your child.

899
01:08:41,907 --> 01:08:44,492
I can't leave Chisholm.

900
01:08:44,493 --> 01:08:49,493
I understand. I do.

901
01:08:49,582 --> 01:08:54,168
But I really think you're
supposed to come with us.

902
01:08:54,169 --> 01:08:54,669
No.

903
01:08:58,841 --> 01:09:01,384
But your wish?

904
01:09:01,385 --> 01:09:03,595
It'll have to stay a wish.

905
01:09:03,596 --> 01:09:08,596
I was born here, I lived here,
I'll die here, but no regrets.

906
01:09:09,018 --> 01:09:13,563
Fifty years ago, for 5 minutes
you came this close.

907
01:09:13,564 --> 01:09:15,273
It would kill some men

908
01:09:15,274 --> 01:09:19,360
to get that close to their
dream and not touch it.

909
01:09:19,361 --> 01:09:21,362
God. They'd consider it
a tragedy.

910
01:09:21,363 --> 01:09:25,408
If I'd only gotten to be
a doctor for five minutes,

911
01:09:25,409 --> 01:09:30,409
now that would have been
a tragedy.

912
01:09:31,582 --> 01:09:36,582
I better be getting home. Alicia
will think I got a girlfriend.

913
01:09:36,879 --> 01:09:40,548
<i>RA Y: And he smiled.</i>

914
01:09:40,549 --> 01:09:45,303
And then I figured, maybe we're
not supposed to take him with us.

915
01:09:45,304 --> 01:09:48,723
I don't know.

916
01:09:48,724 --> 01:09:51,851
I don't know why in the hell
we were supposed to come here.

917
01:09:51,852 --> 01:09:56,564
Maybe it's to find out if one
inning can change the world.

918
01:09:56,565 --> 01:09:57,690
Think it did?

919
01:09:57,691 --> 01:09:59,525
Did for these people.

920
01:09:59,526 --> 01:10:03,738
If he'd gotten a hit, he might
have stayed in baseball.

921
01:10:03,739 --> 01:10:05,948
I don't know.

922
01:10:05,949 --> 01:10:10,949
Oh, your wife called. She wants
you to call her tonight.

923
01:10:11,121 --> 01:10:14,916
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

924
01:10:14,917 --> 01:10:17,669
Ray?

925
01:10:17,670 --> 01:10:21,005
I'm fine.
I'm just so glad it's you.

926
01:10:21,006 --> 01:10:24,676
Listen, I talked to the bank,

927
01:10:24,677 --> 01:10:28,513
and I asked them if we could
miss a payment or two,

928
01:10:28,514 --> 01:10:32,767
and they told me that they had
just sold the note on the farm

929
01:10:32,768 --> 01:10:37,313
to Mark and his partners.

930
01:10:37,314 --> 01:10:39,148
Right.
So they own the paper now.

931
01:10:39,149 --> 01:10:43,611
He says if we don't sell to them,
they're going to foreclose.

932
01:10:43,612 --> 01:10:47,949
Ray, we don't have the money.

933
01:10:47,950 --> 01:10:52,120
Look, I've got to take
Mr. Mann back to Boston first.

934
01:10:52,121 --> 01:10:53,162
Okay? So, it's...

935
01:10:53,163 --> 01:10:55,331
MANN: No.

936
01:10:55,332 --> 01:10:57,291
Wait a second.

937
01:10:57,292 --> 01:11:02,292
I'm going to Iowa with you.

938
01:11:02,756 --> 01:11:07,756
We're coming home.

939
01:11:07,928 --> 01:11:12,348
MANN: Hell, Ican't quit now.
I got to see this ballpark.

940
01:11:12,349 --> 01:11:15,810
RAY: Not everyone can see it.
You might not.

941
01:11:15,811 --> 01:11:20,811
Give it a try.

942
01:11:23,777 --> 01:11:28,777
I need all the karma
I can get right now.

943
01:11:32,327 --> 01:11:34,495
Thanks.
You're the first car by.

944
01:11:34,496 --> 01:11:35,621
How far you going?

945
01:11:35,622 --> 01:11:36,873
How far you going?

946
01:11:36,874 --> 01:11:38,332
Iowa.

947
01:11:38,333 --> 01:11:43,333
If it's okay, I'll just ride along a while.
I play baseball.

948
01:11:44,256 --> 01:11:49,256
Hop in. All right.

949
01:11:54,892 --> 01:11:56,601
I'm looking
for a place to play.

950
01:11:56,602 --> 01:12:00,563
I heard that all through the
Midwest, they have towns with teams.

951
01:12:00,564 --> 01:12:03,858
In some places,
they'll find you a dayjob

952
01:12:03,859 --> 01:12:06,486
so you can play ball
nights and weekends.

953
01:12:06,487 --> 01:12:11,487
It's your lucky day. We're going
someplace kind of like that.

954
01:12:11,700 --> 01:12:13,159
All right.

955
01:12:13,160 --> 01:12:15,953
I'm Ray Kinsella.
This is Terence Mann.

956
01:12:15,954 --> 01:12:17,747
Hi.

957
01:12:17,748 --> 01:12:22,748
I'm Archie Graham.

958
01:12:32,054 --> 01:12:35,556
It's funny the way he described
towns finding you a job

959
01:12:35,557 --> 01:12:38,142
so you could play
on their team.

960
01:12:38,143 --> 01:12:40,520
They haven't done that
for years.

961
01:12:40,521 --> 01:12:44,816
Dad did that for a while,
but that was in the '20s.

962
01:12:44,817 --> 01:12:47,068
What happened to your father?

963
01:12:47,069 --> 01:12:52,069
He never made it as a ballplayer. He
wanted his son to make it for him.

964
01:12:52,074 --> 01:12:57,074
By 10, playing baseball got to be like
eating vegetables or taking out garbage.

965
01:12:58,247 --> 01:13:02,416
When I was 14,
I started to refuse.

966
01:13:02,417 --> 01:13:04,335
Can you believe that?

967
01:13:04,336 --> 01:13:07,797
American boy refusing to have
a catch with his father?

968
01:13:07,798 --> 01:13:11,259
Why 14?

969
01:13:11,260 --> 01:13:13,803
That's when I read The Boat
Rocker by Terence Mann.

970
01:13:13,804 --> 01:13:14,971
Oh, God.

971
01:13:14,972 --> 01:13:16,931
I never played catch
with him again.

972
01:13:16,932 --> 01:13:19,684
That's the crap
people always lay on me.

973
01:13:19,685 --> 01:13:21,894
It's not my fault you wouldn't
play catch with him.

974
01:13:21,895 --> 01:13:22,395
I know.

975
01:13:26,108 --> 01:13:29,277
Anyway, when I was 17,

976
01:13:29,278 --> 01:13:33,573
I packed my things, said
something awful, andleñ.

977
01:13:33,574 --> 01:13:38,244
After a while, I wanted to come
home, but I didn't know how.

978
01:13:38,245 --> 01:13:43,245
Made it back
for the funeral, though.

979
01:13:51,258 --> 01:13:55,219
What was the awful thing
you said?

980
01:13:55,220 --> 01:13:57,847
To your father?

981
01:13:57,848 --> 01:14:00,182
Oh.

982
01:14:00,183 --> 01:14:05,183
I said I could never respect a
man whose hero was a criminal.

983
01:14:05,731 --> 01:14:08,232
Who was his hero?

984
01:14:08,233 --> 01:14:12,570
Shoeless Joe Jackson.

985
01:14:12,571 --> 01:14:15,406
You knew he wasn't a criminal.

986
01:14:15,407 --> 01:14:18,701
Then why did you say it?

987
01:14:18,702 --> 01:14:19,246
I was 17.

988
01:14:24,333 --> 01:14:28,878
The son of a bitch died
before I could take it back.

989
01:14:28,879 --> 01:14:32,423
Before I could tell him,

990
01:14:32,424 --> 01:14:36,427
you know.

991
01:14:36,428 --> 01:14:40,014
He never met my wife.

992
01:14:40,015 --> 01:14:44,185
He never saw his granddaughter.

993
01:14:44,186 --> 01:14:46,562
This is your penance.

994
01:14:46,563 --> 01:14:48,230
I know.

995
01:14:48,231 --> 01:14:50,316
I can't bring my father back.

996
01:14:50,317 --> 01:14:54,779
So the least you can do
is bring back his hero.

997
01:14:54,780 --> 01:14:55,280
Well...

998
01:14:58,867 --> 01:15:03,412
Now I know what
everybody's purpose here is,

999
01:15:03,413 --> 01:15:08,413
except mine.

1000
01:15:09,920 --> 01:15:10,420
Hey.

1001
01:15:36,488 --> 01:15:37,738
KARIN: Daddy!

1002
01:15:37,739 --> 01:15:42,739
Karin, come here.

1003
01:15:42,953 --> 01:15:44,453
ANNIE: Hi!

1004
01:15:44,454 --> 01:15:46,664
Oh, we missed you.

1005
01:15:46,665 --> 01:15:47,999
Are you, okay?

1006
01:15:48,000 --> 01:15:49,959
Yeah. This is Terence Mann.

1007
01:15:49,960 --> 01:15:51,419
Terry.

1008
01:15:51,420 --> 01:15:52,670
Welcome.

1009
01:15:52,671 --> 01:15:54,463
Hi, Terry.

1010
01:15:54,464 --> 01:15:57,925
RAY: And this young fella
is... This is Archie Graham.

1011
01:15:57,926 --> 01:15:59,760
Archie.

1012
01:15:59,761 --> 01:16:01,595
RAY: He's come to practice
with the team.

1013
01:16:01,596 --> 01:16:05,099
He'll be able to do
a lot more than that.

1014
01:16:05,100 --> 01:16:06,809
What does that mean?

1015
01:16:06,810 --> 01:16:11,810
(MEN CHATTERING)

1016
01:16:13,483 --> 01:16:16,569
MAN: What do you say?
What do you say?

1017
01:16:16,570 --> 01:16:19,780
JOE: Hey, Ray. Welcome back.

1018
01:16:19,781 --> 01:16:20,948
Thanks, Joe.

1019
01:16:20,949 --> 01:16:22,199
Oh, my God.

1020
01:16:22,200 --> 01:16:23,284
What?

1021
01:16:23,285 --> 01:16:25,453
That's Shoeless Joe Jackson.

1022
01:16:25,454 --> 01:16:26,871
Of course it is.

1023
01:16:26,872 --> 01:16:28,289
You didn't believe me?

1024
01:16:28,290 --> 01:16:30,207
MANN: I thought I did, but...

1025
01:16:30,208 --> 01:16:33,252
Oh, my God.

1026
01:16:33,253 --> 01:16:35,296
JOE: Hi, Annie. Hi, Joe.

1027
01:16:35,297 --> 01:16:37,298
Good to see you.

1028
01:16:37,299 --> 01:16:40,718
Terry, I'd like you
to meet Shoeless Joe Jackson.

1029
01:16:40,719 --> 01:16:43,929
Joe, Terry Mann.

1030
01:16:43,930 --> 01:16:45,306
It's a pleasure meeting you.

1031
01:16:45,307 --> 01:16:47,266
The pleasure's mine.

1032
01:16:47,267 --> 01:16:50,770
We got tired
of just having practices,

1033
01:16:50,771 --> 01:16:54,815
so we brought another team out
so we'd have some real games.

1034
01:16:54,816 --> 01:16:56,984
I don't mind.

1035
01:16:56,985 --> 01:16:58,194
Where'd they come from?

1036
01:16:58,195 --> 01:16:59,904
Where did we come from?

1037
01:16:59,905 --> 01:17:04,283
So many wanted to play here. We had
to beat them off with a stick.

1038
01:17:04,284 --> 01:17:06,827
Hey, that's Smokey Joe Wood

1039
01:17:06,828 --> 01:17:09,497
and Mel Ott

1040
01:17:09,498 --> 01:17:11,082
and Gil Hodges.

1041
01:17:11,083 --> 01:17:13,042
Ty Cobb wanted to play.

1042
01:17:13,043 --> 01:17:15,336
Nobody could stand him
when we were alive.

1043
01:17:15,337 --> 01:17:20,337
We told him to stick it.

1044
01:17:20,467 --> 01:17:24,011
Hey, are you Graham?

1045
01:17:24,012 --> 01:17:25,554
ARCHIE: Yes, sir.

1046
01:17:25,555 --> 01:17:29,642
Why are you on the sidelines?
Came to play ball, didn't you?

1047
01:17:29,643 --> 01:17:31,727
Yes, sir.

1048
01:17:31,728 --> 01:17:34,647
All right. Well, go warm up.

1049
01:17:34,648 --> 01:17:38,025
Yes, sir.

1050
01:17:38,026 --> 01:17:40,277
Rookies.

1051
01:17:40,278 --> 01:17:43,447
Unbelievable.

1052
01:17:43,448 --> 01:17:46,158
It's more than that.

1053
01:17:46,159 --> 01:17:51,159
It's perfect.

1054
01:18:00,048 --> 01:18:01,674
MAN 1: Ho! MAN 2: Safe!

1055
01:18:01,675 --> 01:18:06,675
(ALL CHEERING)

1056
01:18:11,309 --> 01:18:13,769
Go, Graham! Go, kid!

1057
01:18:13,770 --> 01:18:15,563
Come on, Archie!

1058
01:18:15,564 --> 01:18:17,940
He looks like a baby
next to those guys.

1059
01:18:17,941 --> 01:18:18,441
He is.

1060
01:18:23,572 --> 01:18:27,241
MAN 1: Let's get a hit.

1061
01:18:27,242 --> 01:18:32,242
MAN 2: Let's go.

1062
01:18:32,247 --> 01:18:34,415
Oh!

1063
01:18:34,416 --> 01:18:35,916
MAN: Watch it, boy!

1064
01:18:35,917 --> 01:18:37,084
(BLOWING A RASPBERRY)

1065
01:18:37,085 --> 01:18:38,711
Say hey!

1066
01:18:38,712 --> 01:18:41,589
ANNIE: Don't let him
shake you up. Hang in there!

1067
01:18:41,590 --> 01:18:45,176
Knuckles, what did you throw
at the kid for?

1068
01:18:45,177 --> 01:18:46,927
He winked at me.

1069
01:18:46,928 --> 01:18:50,014
Don't wink, kid.

1070
01:18:50,015 --> 01:18:55,015
Good thing for you
he didn't throw the fastball.

1071
01:18:57,272 --> 01:18:59,565
Let's see that fastball.

1072
01:18:59,566 --> 01:19:02,902
MAN: Let's go. Come on.

1073
01:19:02,903 --> 01:19:05,029
MAN: Yeah! UMPIRE: Ball.

1074
01:19:05,030 --> 01:19:08,782
Hey, ump! Come on.
Give us a break!

1075
01:19:08,783 --> 01:19:10,951
Hey, UmP-

1076
01:19:10,952 --> 01:19:13,787
How about a warning? Sure.

1077
01:19:13,788 --> 01:19:16,040
Watch out you don't get killed.

1078
01:19:16,041 --> 01:19:18,209
Time!

1079
01:19:18,210 --> 01:19:21,128
Time!

1080
01:19:21,129 --> 01:19:23,547
Those first two were
high and tight.

1081
01:19:23,548 --> 01:19:25,966
What will the next one be?

1082
01:19:25,967 --> 01:19:30,804
Well, either low and away
or in my ear.

1083
01:19:30,805 --> 01:19:34,642
He won't want to load the bases.
So look for low and away.

1084
01:19:34,643 --> 01:19:36,977
All right.

1085
01:19:36,978 --> 01:19:40,814
But watch out for in your ear.

1086
01:19:40,815 --> 01:19:42,191
ANNIE: Come on, Archie!
MANN: Let's go, kid!

1087
01:19:42,192 --> 01:19:44,151
Batter, batter, batter, batter!

1088
01:19:44,152 --> 01:19:47,279
Come on, Arch.
It just takes one.

1089
01:19:47,280 --> 01:19:52,280
MAN: Never hit it, kid.

1090
01:19:58,875 --> 01:20:00,334
ANNIE: Yeah. Yeah.

1091
01:20:00,335 --> 01:20:02,169
RAY: That's deep enough.

1092
01:20:02,170 --> 01:20:03,754
MAN: Go! Go!

1093
01:20:03,755 --> 01:20:06,715
Go home!

1094
01:20:06,716 --> 01:20:08,008
Safe!

1095
01:20:08,009 --> 01:20:09,343
Son of a...

1096
01:20:09,344 --> 01:20:12,304
Way to go, Arch! Way to go!

1097
01:20:12,305 --> 01:20:15,349
MAN: Attaboy, Arch!

1098
01:20:15,350 --> 01:20:18,560
This is the wave!

1099
01:20:18,561 --> 01:20:21,188
MAN 1: Way to go, man!
MAN 2: Yeah, Archie.

1100
01:20:21,189 --> 01:20:22,439
MAN: All right.

1101
01:20:22,440 --> 01:20:23,941
That's what we needed.

1102
01:20:23,942 --> 01:20:25,359
Way to go.

1103
01:20:25,360 --> 01:20:30,360
Yeah. Way to go.

1104
01:20:53,555 --> 01:20:58,555
(MEN CHATTERING)

1105
01:21:00,228 --> 01:21:02,938
MAN 1: What is this?

1106
01:21:02,939 --> 01:21:04,440
MAN 2: What is this jerk doing?

1107
01:21:04,441 --> 01:21:05,899
Hi!

1108
01:21:05,900 --> 01:21:06,984
Shit!

1109
01:21:06,985 --> 01:21:08,110
Wreck him.

1110
01:21:08,111 --> 01:21:09,236
MAN: Let me at him!

1111
01:21:09,237 --> 01:21:12,448
You're interrupting
the game, Mark.

1112
01:21:12,449 --> 01:21:15,826
Ray, it's time to put away
your little fantasies

1113
01:21:15,827 --> 01:21:17,119
and come down to Earth.

1114
01:21:17,120 --> 01:21:19,496
It's not a fantasy.
They're real.

1115
01:21:19,497 --> 01:21:21,415
Who is real?

1116
01:21:21,416 --> 01:21:24,918
Shoeless Joe Jackson,
the White Sox, all of them.

1117
01:21:24,919 --> 01:21:26,128
You mean?

1118
01:21:26,129 --> 01:21:28,922
He can't see any of them.

1119
01:21:28,923 --> 01:21:31,967
Well, who is this, Elvis?

1120
01:21:31,968 --> 01:21:34,011
ANNIE: Ray.

1121
01:21:34,012 --> 01:21:36,305
As a matter of fact,
it's Terence Mann.

1122
01:21:36,306 --> 01:21:38,724
How do you do?
I'm the Easter bunny.

1123
01:21:38,725 --> 01:21:41,560
Let's settle this thing now.
You have no money.

1124
01:21:41,561 --> 01:21:44,480
Look. I'm not selling.
You have no money!

1125
01:21:44,481 --> 01:21:48,859
You have a stack of bills! Come
fall, you got no crop to sell.

1126
01:21:48,860 --> 01:21:52,446
I have a deal that allows you
to stay on the land.

1127
01:21:52,447 --> 01:21:55,949
We don't have to sell the farm.

1128
01:21:55,950 --> 01:21:59,161
You'll live
in the house rent-free.

1129
01:21:59,162 --> 01:22:00,621
What about the team?

1130
01:22:00,622 --> 01:22:02,414
Do you realize
how much this land is worth?

1131
01:22:02,415 --> 01:22:06,043
Yeah. Yeah.

1132
01:22:06,044 --> 01:22:07,920
2,200 bucks an acre.

1133
01:22:07,921 --> 01:22:12,299
We can't keep a useless baseball
diamond in rich farmland.

1134
01:22:12,300 --> 01:22:15,302
Read my lips. We're staying, all right?
We're staying.

1135
01:22:15,303 --> 01:22:17,304
Ray, you're bankrupt!

1136
01:22:17,305 --> 01:22:20,140
I'm offering you a way to keep your
home because I love my sister.

1137
01:22:20,141 --> 01:22:24,728
My partners don't care
and are ready to foreclose.

1138
01:22:24,729 --> 01:22:27,815
Daddy, we don't have
to sell the farm.

1139
01:22:27,816 --> 01:22:29,316
Karin, please!

1140
01:22:29,317 --> 01:22:29,983
Just wait!

1141
01:22:29,984 --> 01:22:31,235
Just wait!

1142
01:22:31,236 --> 01:22:34,279
Wait!

1143
01:22:34,280 --> 01:22:37,449
People will come.

1144
01:22:37,450 --> 01:22:39,368
What people, sweetheart?

1145
01:22:39,369 --> 01:22:40,994
From all over.

1146
01:22:40,995 --> 01:22:43,997
They'll just decide
to take a Vacation, see?

1147
01:22:43,998 --> 01:22:46,500
And they'll come to Iowa City.

1148
01:22:46,501 --> 01:22:50,879
They'll think it's really boring.
So they'll want to pay us.

1149
01:22:50,880 --> 01:22:55,880
Like buying a ticket.

1150
01:22:55,927 --> 01:22:58,846
You're not seriously listening
to this, are you?

1151
01:22:58,847 --> 01:23:00,848
Yes.

1152
01:23:00,849 --> 01:23:02,433
Wait a minute.

1153
01:23:02,434 --> 01:23:05,477
Why would anybody pay money
to come here?

1154
01:23:05,478 --> 01:23:07,521
To watch the games.

1155
01:23:07,522 --> 01:23:11,859
Itwill bejust like when they were
little kids a long time ago.

1156
01:23:11,860 --> 01:23:15,612
They'll watch the game
and remember what it was like.

1157
01:23:15,613 --> 01:23:18,115
What the hell
is she talking about?

1158
01:23:18,116 --> 01:23:19,533
People will come.

1159
01:23:19,534 --> 01:23:22,369
All right. This is fascinating,

1160
01:23:22,370 --> 01:23:25,873
but you don't have the money to
bring the mortgage up to date.

1161
01:23:25,874 --> 01:23:29,376
You're still going
to have to sell.

1162
01:23:29,377 --> 01:23:31,378
I'm sorry, Ray.

1163
01:23:31,379 --> 01:23:36,008
We got no choice.

1164
01:23:36,009 --> 01:23:37,718
MANN: Ray.

1165
01:23:37,719 --> 01:23:42,055
People will come, Ray.

1166
01:23:42,056 --> 01:23:46,226
They'll come to Iowa for reasons
they can't even fathom.

1167
01:23:46,227 --> 01:23:50,647
They'll turn up your driveway, not
knowing for sure why they're doing it.

1168
01:23:50,648 --> 01:23:52,149
They'll arrive at your door

1169
01:23:52,150 --> 01:23:56,612
as innocent as children,
longing for the past.

1170
01:23:56,613 --> 01:24:01,283
"Of course, we won't mind
if you look around," youWisay.

1171
01:24:01,284 --> 01:24:03,827
"It's only $20 per person."

1172
01:24:03,828 --> 01:24:07,080
They'll pass over the money
without even thinking about it.

1173
01:24:07,081 --> 01:24:10,417
For it is money they have
and peace they lack.

1174
01:24:10,418 --> 01:24:13,420
Just sign the papers.

1175
01:24:13,421 --> 01:24:17,466
MANN: Then they'll walk out
to the bleachers

1176
01:24:17,467 --> 01:24:22,467
and sit in their shirt sleeves
on a perfect afternoon.

1177
01:24:23,431 --> 01:24:26,683
They'll find
they have reserved seats

1178
01:24:26,684 --> 01:24:29,895
somewhere along
one of the baselines,

1179
01:24:29,896 --> 01:24:32,272
where they sat
when they were children

1180
01:24:32,273 --> 01:24:34,900
and cheered their heroes,

1181
01:24:34,901 --> 01:24:37,110
and they'll watch the game,

1182
01:24:37,111 --> 01:24:41,532
and itwill be as if they dipped
themselves in magic waters.

1183
01:24:41,533 --> 01:24:43,951
The memories will be so thick,

1184
01:24:43,952 --> 01:24:47,079
they'll have to brush them
away from their faces.

1185
01:24:47,080 --> 01:24:51,375
Ray, when the bank opens in the
morning, they'll foreclose.

1186
01:24:51,376 --> 01:24:53,293
People will come, Ray.

1187
01:24:53,294 --> 01:24:57,965
You're broke, Ray. You sell
now, or you lose everything.

1188
01:24:57,966 --> 01:25:02,966
The one constant through all the
years, Ray, has been baseball.

1189
01:25:03,012 --> 01:25:06,807
America has rolled by
like an army of steamrollers.

1190
01:25:06,808 --> 01:25:11,808
It's been erased like a blackboard,
rebuilt, and erased again.

1191
01:25:12,146 --> 01:25:17,109
But baseball has marked
the time.

1192
01:25:17,110 --> 01:25:20,487
This field, this game.

1193
01:25:20,488 --> 01:25:23,532
It's a part of our past, Ray.

1194
01:25:23,533 --> 01:25:27,995
It reminds us of all
that once was good,

1195
01:25:27,996 --> 01:25:31,039
and it could be again.

1196
01:25:31,040 --> 01:25:36,040
Oh, people will come, Ray.

1197
01:25:36,087 --> 01:25:39,464
People will
most definitely come.

1198
01:25:39,465 --> 01:25:43,010
MARK: Ray,
you will lose everything.

1199
01:25:43,011 --> 01:25:48,011
You will be evicted.

1200
01:25:55,940 --> 01:26:00,940
Come on, Ray.

1201
01:26:18,588 --> 01:26:20,213
I'm not signing.

1202
01:26:20,214 --> 01:26:23,175
You're crazy. Absolutely nuts!

1203
01:26:23,176 --> 01:26:24,468
I can't do it, pal.

1204
01:26:24,469 --> 01:26:26,637
I mean,
you build a baseball field

1205
01:26:26,638 --> 01:26:28,347
I mean,
you build a baseball field

1206
01:26:28,348 --> 01:26:31,516
in the middle of nowhere,
and you stare at nothing.

1207
01:26:31,517 --> 01:26:34,561
It's not nothing. Your daughter's
turned into a space case.

1208
01:26:34,562 --> 01:26:38,023
Get your hands off her!

1209
01:26:38,024 --> 01:26:43,024
ANNIE: Karin?

1210
01:26:44,572 --> 01:26:47,157
ANNIE: Is she all right?
Is she breathing?

1211
01:26:47,158 --> 01:26:52,158
MANN: Should I get the car?

1212
01:26:54,165 --> 01:26:57,584
I'm going to call Emergency.

1213
01:26:57,585 --> 01:26:59,586
Annie, wait.

1214
01:26:59,587 --> 01:27:00,087
What?

1215
01:27:18,064 --> 01:27:23,064
Just wait.

1216
01:27:37,875 --> 01:27:39,459
What have we got here?

1217
01:27:39,460 --> 01:27:40,072
She fell.

1218
01:27:48,469 --> 01:27:51,805
GRAHAM: This child's choking
to death. Get her up.

1219
01:27:51,806 --> 01:27:54,391
Hold her steady now.

1220
01:27:54,392 --> 01:27:59,392
(KARIN COUGHING)

1221
01:27:59,647 --> 01:28:02,941
Hot dog. Stuck in her throat.

1222
01:28:02,942 --> 01:28:04,568
She'll be all right.

1223
01:28:04,569 --> 01:28:09,569
She'll be turning handsprings
before you know it.

1224
01:28:11,868 --> 01:28:14,786
Thank you, Doc.

1225
01:28:14,787 --> 01:28:16,663
No, son.

1226
01:28:16,664 --> 01:28:20,834
Thank you.

1227
01:28:20,835 --> 01:28:23,336
Oh, my God. You can't go back.

1228
01:28:23,337 --> 01:28:25,130
Hey, it's all right.

1229
01:28:25,131 --> 01:28:30,131
I'm sorry. It's all right.

1230
01:28:32,054 --> 01:28:34,514
I best be getting on home

1231
01:28:34,515 --> 01:28:39,515
before Alicia begins to think
I got a girlfriend.

1232
01:28:43,024 --> 01:28:44,941
Hey, D0c.

1233
01:28:44,942 --> 01:28:48,445
Good work, Doc.

1234
01:28:48,446 --> 01:28:53,033
Nice going, Doc.

1235
01:28:53,034 --> 01:28:57,037
Going to miss you, Doc.

1236
01:28:57,038 --> 01:28:59,664
Win one for me one day,
will you, boys?

1237
01:28:59,665 --> 01:29:01,041
Okay, Doc.

1238
01:29:01,042 --> 01:29:01,542
Yeah.

1239
01:29:09,383 --> 01:29:14,383
When did these ballplayers
get here?

1240
01:29:17,683 --> 01:29:22,683
JOE: Hey, rookie!

1241
01:29:30,822 --> 01:29:35,822
You were good.

1242
01:29:46,504 --> 01:29:50,590
Do not sell this farm, Ray.
You got to keep this farm.

1243
01:29:50,591 --> 01:29:54,970
You've had a rough day. Go inside
and get something cold to drink.

1244
01:29:54,971 --> 01:29:58,974
Yeah. That's a good idea.

1245
01:29:58,975 --> 01:30:03,975
Don't sell the farm, Ray.

1246
01:30:10,069 --> 01:30:12,279
Ray?

1247
01:30:12,280 --> 01:30:14,406
We're going to call it a day.

1248
01:30:14,407 --> 01:30:16,032
See you tomorrow.

1249
01:30:16,033 --> 01:30:16,533
Okay.

1250
01:30:21,539 --> 01:30:26,539
Hey, do you want
to come with us?

1251
01:30:27,795 --> 01:30:29,462
You mean it?

1252
01:30:29,463 --> 01:30:32,007
No, not you.

1253
01:30:32,008 --> 01:30:32,508
Him.

1254
01:30:36,637 --> 01:30:38,805
Him? Come with you?

1255
01:30:38,806 --> 01:30:39,973
JOE: Out there.

1256
01:30:39,974 --> 01:30:41,308
What is out there?

1257
01:30:41,309 --> 01:30:42,726
Come and find out.

1258
01:30:42,727 --> 01:30:44,519
Wait a second. Why him?

1259
01:30:44,520 --> 01:30:46,980
I built this field. You wouldn't
be here if it weren't for me.

1260
01:30:46,981 --> 01:30:48,899
Ray, I'm unattached.
You have a family.

1261
01:30:48,900 --> 01:30:52,819
I want to know
what's out there.

1262
01:30:52,820 --> 01:30:56,656
But you're not invited.

1263
01:30:56,657 --> 01:30:59,701
Not invited? What do you mean
I'm not invited?

1264
01:30:59,702 --> 01:31:03,038
That's my corn out there. You
guys are guests in my corn.

1265
01:31:03,039 --> 01:31:05,165
I've done everything
I've been asked to do.

1266
01:31:05,166 --> 01:31:07,500
I didn't understand it,
but I've done it.

1267
01:31:07,501 --> 01:31:09,502
I haven't once asked
what's in it for me.

1268
01:31:09,503 --> 01:31:10,670
What are you saying?

1269
01:31:10,671 --> 01:31:14,382
I'm saying,
"What's in it for me?"

1270
01:31:14,383 --> 01:31:16,551
Is that why you did this?

1271
01:31:16,552 --> 01:31:17,052
Foryou?

1272
01:31:22,808 --> 01:31:27,808
I think you'd better
stay here, Ray.

1273
01:31:28,856 --> 01:31:31,775
Why?

1274
01:31:31,776 --> 01:31:34,861
There's a reason they chose me,

1275
01:31:34,862 --> 01:31:38,865
just as there's a reason
they chose this field.

1276
01:31:38,866 --> 01:31:40,700
MANN: I gave that interview.

1277
01:31:40,701 --> 01:31:42,827
What interview?
What are you talking about?

1278
01:31:42,828 --> 01:31:47,828
The one about Ebbets Field, the one
that sent you to Boston to find me.

1279
01:31:50,002 --> 01:31:51,670
You lied to me.

1280
01:31:51,671 --> 01:31:54,714
You were kidnapping me at the time.
You lied.

1281
01:31:54,715 --> 01:31:59,344
You said your finger was a gun.

1282
01:31:59,345 --> 01:32:01,137
That's a good point.

1283
01:32:01,138 --> 01:32:04,724
Ray.

1284
01:32:04,725 --> 01:32:07,394
Ray.

1285
01:32:07,395 --> 01:32:11,564
Listen to me, Ray.
Listen to me.

1286
01:32:11,565 --> 01:32:14,401
There is something out there,

1287
01:32:14,402 --> 01:32:17,404
and if I have the courage
to go through with this,

1288
01:32:17,405 --> 01:32:21,241
what a story it'll make.

1289
01:32:21,242 --> 01:32:26,242
"Shoeless Joe Jackson comes
to Iowa."

1290
01:32:33,045 --> 01:32:34,754
What? Are you going
to write about it?

1291
01:32:34,755 --> 01:32:36,965
You bet I'll write about it.

1292
01:32:36,966 --> 01:32:39,759
You're going to write about it.

1293
01:32:39,760 --> 01:32:44,760
That's what I do.

1294
01:32:45,516 --> 01:32:46,016
Good.

1295
01:32:50,021 --> 01:32:50,521
Good.

1296
01:33:01,365 --> 01:33:06,365
ANNIE: Honey?

1297
01:33:06,912 --> 01:33:09,622
Honey, where's he going?

1298
01:33:09,623 --> 01:33:12,292
Terry's been invited
to go out with the others.

1299
01:33:12,293 --> 01:33:14,252
How are you feeling,
sweetheart?

1300
01:33:14,253 --> 01:33:15,628
Stupid.

1301
01:33:15,629 --> 01:33:16,921
You mean out?

1302
01:33:16,922 --> 01:33:19,174
Yeah.

1303
01:33:19,175 --> 01:33:21,051
Out.

1304
01:33:21,052 --> 01:33:24,512
ANNIE: Far out.

1305
01:33:24,513 --> 01:33:27,057
I want a full description.

1306
01:33:27,058 --> 01:33:31,644
Take care of this family.

1307
01:33:31,645 --> 01:33:36,645
ANNIE: Be careful.

1308
01:34:32,206 --> 01:34:32,706
Bye.

1309
01:34:36,544 --> 01:34:37,044
What?

1310
01:34:44,885 --> 01:34:47,762
What are you grinning at,
you ghost?

1311
01:34:47,763 --> 01:34:51,808
"If you build it,"

1312
01:34:51,809 --> 01:34:56,809
"he will come."

1313
01:35:05,406 --> 01:35:07,490
Oh, my God.

1314
01:35:07,491 --> 01:35:12,491
What? What is it?

1315
01:35:13,080 --> 01:35:18,080
It's my father.

1316
01:35:19,920 --> 01:35:22,881
"Ease his pain."

1317
01:35:22,882 --> 01:35:27,719
ANNIE: "Go the distance."

1318
01:35:27,720 --> 01:35:32,720
RAY: It was you.

1319
01:35:33,100 --> 01:35:34,851
No, Ray.

1320
01:35:34,852 --> 01:35:39,852
It was you.

1321
01:36:02,713 --> 01:36:05,340
RAY: My God. I...

1322
01:36:05,341 --> 01:36:10,341
I only saw him years later
when he was worn down by life.

1323
01:36:10,846 --> 01:36:14,140
Look at him.

1324
01:36:14,141 --> 01:36:19,141
He's got his whole life in front of him,
and I'm not even a glint in his eye.

1325
01:36:23,484 --> 01:36:27,362
What do I say to him?

1326
01:36:27,363 --> 01:36:32,363
ANNIE: Why don't you introduce
him to his granddaughter?

1327
01:36:33,702 --> 01:36:36,162
JOHN: Hi.

1328
01:36:36,163 --> 01:36:37,747
Hi.

1329
01:36:37,748 --> 01:36:41,084
I just wanted to thank you folks
for putting up this field,

1330
01:36:41,085 --> 01:36:43,544
letting us play here.

1331
01:36:43,545 --> 01:36:47,340
I'm John Kinsella.

1332
01:36:47,341 --> 01:36:50,176
I'm Ray.

1333
01:36:50,177 --> 01:36:52,887
My wife Annie. Hi.

1334
01:36:52,888 --> 01:36:54,806
This is my daughter Karin.

1335
01:36:54,807 --> 01:36:59,519
Karin, this is my...

1336
01:36:59,520 --> 01:37:02,063
This is John.

1337
01:37:02,064 --> 01:37:05,775
KARIN: Hi, John.

1338
01:37:05,776 --> 01:37:09,821
Hiya, Karin.

1339
01:37:09,822 --> 01:37:14,158
Well, we're going to let
you two talk.

1340
01:37:14,159 --> 01:37:15,952
I mean, if all these people
are going to come,

1341
01:37:15,953 --> 01:37:20,290
we got a lot of work to do.

1342
01:37:20,291 --> 01:37:23,626
It was very nice meeting you.

1343
01:37:23,627 --> 01:37:26,129
Ma'am.

1344
01:37:26,130 --> 01:37:31,130
Come on, hon.

1345
01:37:42,354 --> 01:37:45,481
You catch a good game.

1346
01:37:45,482 --> 01:37:49,152
Thank you.

1347
01:37:49,153 --> 01:37:53,239
It's so beautiful here.

1348
01:37:53,240 --> 01:37:56,784
For me...

1349
01:37:56,785 --> 01:38:01,785
Well, for me it's like
a dream come true.

1350
01:38:03,417 --> 01:38:08,417
Can I ask you something?

1351
01:38:09,089 --> 01:38:14,089
Is... Is this heaven?

1352
01:38:15,304 --> 01:38:18,639
It's Iowa.

1353
01:38:18,640 --> 01:38:20,558
Iowa?

1354
01:38:20,559 --> 01:38:21,059
Yeah.

1355
01:38:24,897 --> 01:38:29,897
I could have sworn
it was heaven.

1356
01:38:35,616 --> 01:38:37,700
Is...

1357
01:38:37,701 --> 01:38:41,537
Is there a heaven?

1358
01:38:41,538 --> 01:38:44,791
Oh, yeah.

1359
01:38:44,792 --> 01:38:49,792
It's the place
dreams come true.

1360
01:39:07,189 --> 01:39:12,189
Maybe this is heaven.

1361
01:39:13,987 --> 01:39:15,947
Well...

1362
01:39:15,948 --> 01:39:19,992
Good night, Ray.

1363
01:39:19,993 --> 01:39:24,993
Good night, John.

1364
01:39:31,880 --> 01:39:36,880
RAY: Hey, Dad?

1365
01:39:37,636 --> 01:39:42,098
You want to have a catch?

1366
01:39:42,099 --> 01:39:47,099
I'd like that.
